overall revenue, but 16 percent of profits.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">There=E2=
=80=99s an argument that Larsson and Serrano shouldn=E2=80=99t be relaunchi=
ng ready-to-wear altogether: If the previous regime couldn=E2=80=99t make i=
t work with the current designers of <em>Prada, Ala=C3=AFa, and Chanel</em>=
, how can anybody? But Leoni was a big hire, and the internet will be waiti=
ng for this collection to land on Ssense. And a runway show still offers a =
singular
marketing opportunity that can=E2=80=99t be supplanted by <strong>Jeremy Al=
len White</strong> in his underwear.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>B=
ut Calvin Klein doesn=E2=80=99t have a marketing problem; it has a product =
problem. People wear the underwear out of habit, but it=E2=80=99s been ages=
 since the jeans were top of mind. Did Leoni=E2=80=99s show on Friday manag=
e to change that? Well, a <em>first</em> collection should be considered as=
 such, and Leoni=E2=80=99s job is much harder at a place like PVH than at a=
 luxury goods
firm. Funnily enough, though, the pieces I liked most from Leoni=E2=80=99s =
debut collection were the ones pulled from Simons=E2=80=99s Calvin: the pla=
id shirts, denim, and cowboy boots. In <em>The New York Times</em>, Leoni p=
romised sexiness, and this was the closest she got.</p></div>
